Post-mortem:

Overall: Outside the Commander Championship I felt my deck power level generally matched the power level of the decks around me, the vast majority of which were 75%-ish builds. The exception was Don who plays in a much more powerful meta and whose decks match that, and even then I never felt hopelessly outmatched. I saw way more Crypts and Vaults than I see back home. Nobody runs them here really, not because they're not good or don't have them, but because they just don't, myself included. I'm fine with that locally, but I maybe should make a mental note to throw them into decks for Vegas next year just so I'm not bringing piss to a shit fight. I also saw more casual useage of theft effects than I generally see at home. That might be a result of everyone locally packing a Homeward Path in every single deck to the point people have stopped running things like Control Magic for value. I find meta things like that fascinating, but it's clearly a local abberation. My existing opinion on partners has been reinforced ten-fold. They're the worst thing to happen to the format since I've been playing. They encourage the worst kind of homogenized goodstuff bullshit and we'd be better off if they'd never been printed.

Edric: Only played it twice. It's probably the deck that most matches Don's meta and hung in fairly well with Blood Pod. To use my grandfather's vernacular think I need to shit or get off the pot with it; it's too fast for a 75%-ish meta, but I'm still pulling punches with the build in an attempt to pretend it's fair. I need to either just take it apart, or go all-in and buy a Capture of Jingzhou and make it the deck I play against people with baller decks.

Wasitora: Built it as I was leaving and saw the first games in Vegas. I really like the deck and I'm gonna keep it around. There were a couple of times I was able to just extra combat steps people into oblivion. Deck needs more ramp, and I gotta figure out my curve. The creatures that work best with attack steps are 5-6 drops, and I have way too many, but the low curve bodies aren't that effective if they don't have evasion. I'll make some tweaks, and it's the kind of deck where there will be constantly new cards that can work with it each set, so that's always good.

Mina and Denn: I don't play this deck enough, but I like how it has so many win conditions. It needs a fresh pass because I think I might have too much ramp as weird as that sounds. By the time I cast Boundless Realms for example more often than not it's not fully effective because I've already landfalled enough other lands.

Glissa: Vegas quelled my inner conflict about Torment. Games gotta end, but I felt bad winning with Torment in the past. Nobody was ever salty about it though, and seeing that helped. Besides, if you let me play an Coffers and have enough swamps to use it and then let me draw or tutor a Torment for 20 maybe you don't deserve to win. I think I'm fine with that, particularly in a deck I love but that struggles to close out games.

Djeru: Was a shitshow against Jason's Rubinia deck and another dude's flip Jace deck just becuase all three had anti-synergy that made none of them work, but that kinda thing happens. I still like it for how janky it is, and I won a game with it at local shops over the week in Minneapolis and in Vegas so that's good enough for me.
Reki: Fast becoming my favorite deck. It's not anything complicated, but I get to play cards nobody has heard of that are uber synergystic.

Deck Post-Mortem:

Rakdos, Jeleva, Mer Ber are the decks I've had in paper the longest and haven't changed much.
Mairsil I've had the parts for a few months, but has physically shared the paper land base with Jeleva so it's a pain to try to play both in the same session.
Nath, Ashling, Atraxa were papered just before vegas.
(King Macar is proably next since I have most of the cards)

I didn't keep track of results as well as Dana, but from memory...
Jeleva, I've switched out some extra turn spells in favor of signets for a faster start and fewer 4-turns-in-a-row performances since they get embarrassing. However, the new buy-a-box extra turn card that shuffles back in will be going into Jeleva.
Rakdos and Mer Ber did their usual thing. Mirage Mirror is good.
Nath, I'm taking Sadistic Hypnotist out as a sideboard card since it's the only non-elf creature and it leaves the option of whether to play that combo for "harder" games.
Mairsil is hard to learn how to pilot, but once you figure it out, he can be a lot of fun. Very chaotic in your options, which I enjoy so I don't use Entomb effects.
Ashling the Pilgrim, surprisingly, won 4 out of 7 games if I'm remembering correctly. Mana Geyser is a card.
Atraxa was almost spectacular in the single game it played, which is good enough for me. The combo was interrupted by removal, but the group got to see what could have happened and feel the thrill.
side note: i used to have Krenko and Ezuri Claw in paper, but got boring to play and partially disassembled

meren rats: only had one decent game with it the whole time, the rest were creatureless draws or I stumbled on mana, which makes it really hard to do anything in general. Thinking I should put in that third ramp spell or another draw spell over a removal slot now

mech production breya: does silly things and people find it hard to know what to do with the board state I create sometimes, but it’s power is pretty high and it does it’s thing. Very happy with where it is right now, and is definitely where my vedalken orrery belongs because I can then cast mech production at eot to win off it instead of just waiting.

gonti: mono black good stuff is good it turns out. I didn’t really like the infinite win I pulled off with it but at that point if I didn’t do it then I was going to win off the lili ult anyway so at least it finished it sooner. A special thanks to <@U28TLDP0R> for milling me twice into beacon of unrest for some great creatures

kess: the deck is as directionless as it has felt for a while now, I need to pick a new theme besides wheels, as it isn’t super effective that way currently. Maybe I should just embrace the idea of “hive mind” and cast some really silly spells

atraxa: mana base needs heavy upgrading for how tough the pips are in the deck it turns out, I really dig the synergies there and it needs a better tutoring suite to make it as powerful as it really needs to be to fight modern decks. Still, janky counters is hilarious to watch people try to deal with and that was my goal from the beginning. 

angry bobo: didn’t play much with him as he is my most proxied deck and it felt weird doing it. I like the recurrsion that I put in as it allows me to grab the return from graveyard spells or lands from there much more consistant. Almost killing max with magus of the moon and barrel down sokuzen is still one of the best faces he made that weekend. Only topped by him wondering what my no turns deck was all about.
